Cycle is caused by second `A` constructor. Let&#39;s analyze it:

    class A {
    
        A(x,y,z,m){
            /* do the necessary initialization */
        }
    
        A (x, y, z){
            this(x,y,z,m(new A(x,y,z)))
        }
    }

On second constructor, you have three params, and the unique line indicates a call to first constructor, with a new `m` instance. But the problem is this instance calls second constructor again, so you execute the same again: the unique line calls first constructor, with a new `m` instance that calls second constructor... and so on. Then, this execution will be interrupted by a `java.lang.StackOverflowError` exception. I suggest you must only use first constructor and remove the second one.

